1
00:00:05,942 --> 00:00:08,704
So, hello, my name is Frederic Renal.

2
00:00:09,384 --> 00:00:14,088
I'm the creator and programmer of the first Alone in the Dark.

3
00:00:15,469 --> 00:00:15,849
And I'm here...

4
00:00:15,869 --> 00:00:16,230
Thank you.

5
00:00:17,090 --> 00:00:17,491
Thank you.

6
00:00:17,551 --> 00:00:17,811
Thank you.

7
00:00:22,454 --> 00:00:27,276
And I'm here to tell you the story of the making of this game.

8
00:00:27,896 --> 00:00:35,179
And I'm very, very happy to be here, especially this year, 2012, because it's the 20th anniversary

9
00:00:35,239 --> 00:00:35,759
of this game.

10
00:00:35,999 --> 00:00:40,601
Exactly 20 years ago, I was working 15 hours a day to try to make...

11
00:00:41,641 --> 00:00:47,786
this exists. So before going deep inside the conception of the game, I just want to tell

12
00:00:47,806 --> 00:00:53,671
you a few things about me before this game, because it's important, because it helps to

13
00:00:53,731 --> 00:00:56,654
understand from where came the inspiration.

14
00:00:59,289 --> 00:01:03,732
Early 80s, my father got a computer shop,

15
00:01:03,752 --> 00:01:05,234
it was named Videomatique.

16
00:01:06,034 --> 00:01:07,716
It was in France, I'm French.

17
00:01:08,657 --> 00:01:11,959
And I was helping customers with computers,

18
00:01:12,039 --> 00:01:13,741
repairing their computers.

19
00:01:14,925 --> 00:01:21,266
And here I made a game in 88, which was Popcorn.

20
00:01:21,326 --> 00:01:22,766
It was a breakout freeware.

21
00:01:23,106 --> 00:01:28,587
Nothing very important, but Infogrames saw this game and

22
00:01:28,907 --> 00:01:32,528
called me to work at Infogrames.

23
00:01:32,928 --> 00:01:36,309
But something which is the most important thing is that

24
00:01:36,769 --> 00:01:41,870
my father's shop was also a VHS movie tape rental shop.

25
00:01:42,890 --> 00:01:45,931
So I was working days and nights in this shop.

26
00:01:46,111 --> 00:01:50,672
So at night, when I was bored programming, I watched movies.

27
00:01:51,252 --> 00:01:55,773
I maybe watched all the movies I can find in the shop.

28
00:01:55,813 --> 00:01:59,194
And I was very, very fond of all the horror movies.

29
00:01:59,254 --> 00:02:01,655
I was 20-plus years old at this time.

30
00:02:02,175 --> 00:02:03,535
And my heroes were.

31
00:02:04,836 --> 00:02:09,542
George Romero, Dario Argento, I loved all those movies.

32
00:02:09,562 --> 00:02:11,224
I love zombies.

33
00:02:11,665 --> 00:02:16,672
And something which is very interesting is the structure of that kind of movies,

34
00:02:17,072 --> 00:02:21,258
all the 70s horror movies, is that usually you are...

35
00:02:21,939 --> 00:02:25,301
one guy or a group of guy entering a special environment

36
00:02:25,761 --> 00:02:27,162
and just tries to survive.

37
00:02:27,662 --> 00:02:30,324
Look at the headline of Amityville.

38
00:02:30,804 --> 00:02:32,946
The scenario of Alone in the Dark is written on it.

39
00:02:33,066 --> 00:02:34,947
For God's sake, just get out.

40
00:02:35,607 --> 00:02:38,329
And that was the main inspiration for that.

41
00:02:38,409 --> 00:02:42,092
But I didn't know that at this time.

42
00:02:42,592 --> 00:02:47,855
I also, I was 20 years old, playing a lot of role playing

43
00:02:47,875 --> 00:02:50,137
game also with my friend at this time.

44
00:02:51,017 --> 00:02:54,879
And, uh, especially Dungeon and Dragon, I played a little bit,

45
00:02:55,019 --> 00:02:57,560
uh, Call of Cthulhu, because actually I didn't like it.

46
00:02:57,660 --> 00:03:01,242
The character x, uh, character sheet was so huge,

47
00:03:01,262 --> 00:03:03,503
and it was so, uh, difficult.

48
00:03:04,063 --> 00:03:07,284
Okay, but I'll be back, uh, on, um, on that later.

49
00:03:07,685 --> 00:03:09,645
So, I joined Infogrames in, uh, 99.

50
00:03:11,322 --> 00:03:17,404
I was doing some programming stuff, low-level function, graphical function and everything.

51
00:03:17,884 --> 00:03:23,907
And one day, I was involved in the conversion of a game, which is AlphaWaze.

52
00:03:23,967 --> 00:03:25,507
It was named Continuum here.

53
00:03:26,067 --> 00:03:26,708
We were in the 90s.

54
00:03:28,308 --> 00:03:30,450
The name of the game was The Cube at this time.

55
00:03:30,510 --> 00:03:33,112
Christophe de Dinoshin is the creator of this game.

56
00:03:33,412 --> 00:03:38,256
And I did the conversion, the port, from the Atari ST to PC.

57
00:03:38,776 --> 00:03:40,117
It was all ASM code.

58
00:03:40,497 --> 00:03:44,360
So I worked for six months on this game.

59
00:03:45,376 --> 00:03:50,281
And so I spent six months inside a rotating cube.

60
00:03:50,641 --> 00:03:51,562
Because it was a game.

61
00:03:51,602 --> 00:03:54,825
You can see it at the GDC play part.

62
00:03:54,865 --> 00:03:56,567
There is a demonstration of this game.

63
00:03:56,867 --> 00:03:58,348
It's a bouncing shape.

64
00:03:58,849 --> 00:04:01,291
And it's the first 3D platform game.

65
00:04:02,112 --> 00:04:05,734
And so I spent six months with this rotating cube around me.

66
00:04:06,255 --> 00:04:07,856
And it obsessed me.

67
00:04:08,456 --> 00:04:11,679
I was always thinking, there is something to do with 3D.

68
00:04:13,020 --> 00:04:17,864
And I didn't know yet quite exactly, but my imagination.

69
00:04:18,962 --> 00:04:23,664
was very, very motivated, said, OK, we can modelize something

70
00:04:23,944 --> 00:04:28,245
more and more better than just small shapes like this.

71
00:04:28,685 --> 00:04:31,946
And I was thinking about 3D characters.

72
00:04:32,266 --> 00:04:33,807
And I said, OK, there is something

73
00:04:33,887 --> 00:04:35,667
to do with 3D characters.

74
00:04:35,747 --> 00:04:39,128
And one day, it came quite quickly.

75
00:04:39,268 --> 00:04:41,829
Everything went very smoothly and logically.

76
00:04:42,309 --> 00:04:44,350
And one day, I said, I have this idea.

77
00:04:45,617 --> 00:04:47,418
It was my first vision of the game.

78
00:04:47,799 --> 00:04:51,983
I wanted to have articulated and skinned 3D characters

79
00:04:52,663 --> 00:04:55,266
with first 3D zombies.

80
00:04:55,606 --> 00:04:57,028
I was really, really excited.

81
00:04:57,068 --> 00:04:59,150
OK, now it's possible.

82
00:04:59,490 --> 00:05:02,413
I can do a game with 3D zombies.

83
00:05:03,374 --> 00:05:06,857
My favorite game at this time were adventure and action

84
00:05:06,897 --> 00:05:07,118
games.

85
00:05:08,631 --> 00:05:13,734
had to be an adventure game with some action.

86
00:05:14,275 --> 00:05:16,276
I'll go deeper in that later.

87
00:05:17,096 --> 00:05:22,280
And about how to play, because we were in the early 90s,

88
00:05:23,641 --> 00:05:26,803
we couldn't manage many characters, dialogues,

89
00:05:26,843 --> 00:05:27,383
and everything.

90
00:05:27,403 --> 00:05:28,764
Say, OK, it's a game.

91
00:05:28,884 --> 00:05:30,105
You are just alone.

92
00:05:30,265 --> 00:05:32,246
Because it was just convenient.

93
00:05:32,426 --> 00:05:36,269
Say, no human interactions, no dialogue, things like that.

94
00:05:37,367 --> 00:05:43,473
And when can this game exist?

95
00:05:43,553 --> 00:05:51,221
The year 1920 is very convenient because there is electricity, so you can have light,

96
00:05:51,981 --> 00:05:56,145
but there is no electronics, there is no complicated stuff.

97
00:05:56,366 --> 00:05:58,368
So it was perfect for...

98
00:05:59,373 --> 00:06:04,335
For the date, the place, the idea came from horror movies,

99
00:06:04,715 --> 00:06:09,578
and an old mansion, an old haunted manor for the place.

100
00:06:10,298 --> 00:06:13,940
And the scenario, just get out alive.

101
00:06:14,260 --> 00:06:16,181
You enter the situation, you enter the house,

102
00:06:16,721 --> 00:06:20,643
and you just have to exit the house alive.

103
00:06:21,844 --> 00:06:28,450
Something I knew since the beginning is that I needed to have some text to read because

104
00:06:30,152 --> 00:06:36,818
to make something very scary, and especially back in at this time, with just a few polygons,

105
00:06:36,978 --> 00:06:42,863
that's something that is not very frightening. So I knew that I needed the text to put a

106
00:06:42,983 --> 00:06:48,588
situation to have a very heavy background story for the game.

107
00:06:50,090 --> 00:06:53,733
And so something I understood very quickly, too,

108
00:06:53,893 --> 00:06:59,417
is that with the polygons, the number of polygons,

109
00:06:59,457 --> 00:07:02,660
the amount of polygons I can put in the engine at this time

110
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:05,262
was not very, very big.

111
00:07:05,682 --> 00:07:12,747
So I thought that I need some 3D backgrounds.

112
00:07:13,765 --> 00:07:18,788
but which were not made with polygons. So, uh, I had the idea,

113
00:07:18,808 --> 00:07:24,071
I can take pictures of a real mansion, an old one, and then

114
00:07:24,171 --> 00:07:29,033
made my 3D fits on those picture to have those, uh, 3D, uh,

115
00:07:29,413 --> 00:07:33,896
characters, uh, inside the, uh, the game. Actually, you, you

116
00:07:33,936 --> 00:07:37,217
know the game, it's not like this at the end, and, uh, you

117
00:07:37,237 --> 00:07:38,078
will see, uh, why.

118
00:07:42,889 --> 00:07:47,153
OK, so I had at Infogrames a good friend who was named Didier

119
00:07:47,253 --> 00:07:50,877
Chamfret, and I explained him my vision of the game.

120
00:07:51,638 --> 00:07:56,883
3D zombies in a house, and you need to get out and fight

121
00:07:56,943 --> 00:07:59,205
monsters in this adventure game.

122
00:07:59,366 --> 00:08:01,568
And Didier did this drawing.

123
00:08:02,289 --> 00:08:05,152
And this is really the first.

124
00:08:06,295 --> 00:08:11,259
thing that was done on Alone in the Dark, and this was very a good inspiration.

125
00:08:11,279 --> 00:08:18,325
I kept, we kept this drawing above my desk for the world development, each time somebody

126
00:08:18,365 --> 00:08:21,648
was asking, you are working on what, say, at this look.

127
00:08:24,130 --> 00:08:27,733
And actually Infogrames didn't really believe in it at this time.

128
00:08:29,054 --> 00:08:35,979
So, for the first time of my life, because I did games for the previous 10 years before,

129
00:08:36,919 --> 00:08:42,063
it was the first time where the amount of work seems very huge, because...

130
00:08:42,664 --> 00:08:45,766
Usually, you think about the game with a few sprites and everything.

131
00:08:45,806 --> 00:08:49,549
You do a quick prototype in two hours to see how the game works.

132
00:08:50,010 --> 00:08:53,392
But I needed things that just didn't exist at this time.

133
00:08:54,353 --> 00:08:57,215
3D characters, articulation, it means tools.

134
00:08:57,656 --> 00:08:57,716
So

135
00:08:59,797 --> 00:09:01,820
I started my first tool.

136
00:09:01,960 --> 00:09:06,084
I needed a 3D modeler, but we were early 90s.

137
00:09:06,104 --> 00:09:08,327
I never saw a professional modeler.

138
00:09:08,847 --> 00:09:11,410
Modelers that existed at this time

139
00:09:11,530 --> 00:09:16,015
were quite simple with those three views to edit a few things.

140
00:09:16,055 --> 00:09:16,195
So.

141
00:09:17,358 --> 00:09:21,160
I needed mine, so I said, OK, let's do a modeler.

142
00:09:21,661 --> 00:09:26,504
And as I told you, I was so obsessed by this 3D rotating

143
00:09:26,564 --> 00:09:30,186
cube that I decided to make my own editor.

144
00:09:30,866 --> 00:09:32,387
And in this editor, you

145
00:09:33,899 --> 00:09:35,279
edit your mesh.

146
00:09:35,960 --> 00:09:38,962
But in just one 3D view, everything

147
00:09:39,042 --> 00:09:41,444
is based on this rotated cube.

148
00:09:41,724 --> 00:09:46,808
And you can move a grid inside of it, placing your points,

149
00:09:47,108 --> 00:09:49,970
drawing lines, and polygon.

150
00:09:50,410 --> 00:09:52,311
The tool was in EGA mode.

151
00:09:52,391 --> 00:09:54,933
For those who know the PC at this time,

152
00:09:54,993 --> 00:09:56,694
it was a high resolution mode, 640 by 350.

153
00:09:56,754 --> 00:09:57,975
Pixels were not square.

154
00:10:02,241 --> 00:10:07,944
And these tools allow us to create the model of the game,

155
00:10:08,265 --> 00:10:10,306
the object, the characters, and everything.

156
00:10:11,246 --> 00:10:15,629
Put not texture, because it was flat polygons.

157
00:10:15,689 --> 00:10:20,392
But I did some kind of materials on them to be able

158
00:10:20,432 --> 00:10:23,033
to have a little bit of variety for them.

159
00:10:23,653 --> 00:10:27,376
And with this tool, you can also edit real-time animation.

160
00:10:27,916 --> 00:10:30,918
Again, I'll be back on this later.

161
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:42,311
So I needed also another tool, a tool to be able to edit the backgrounds, actually, to

162
00:10:42,431 --> 00:10:47,817
put collisions and to make fit my 3D function on the picture.

163
00:10:49,539 --> 00:10:55,163
Because, as I told you, I was sure that I cannot use polygons for the background, because

164
00:10:55,183 --> 00:11:01,707
it was not, I couldn't put enough polygons to have a very nice north scenery.

165
00:11:02,448 --> 00:11:08,472
So I did this tool to, where you were able to put some wireframe cubes in it, trying

166
00:11:08,552 --> 00:11:14,576
to make them, to make the collision fits to the, on the imported pictures.

167
00:11:15,217 --> 00:11:21,360
Something that you need also to remember is that in 91, digital camera didn't exist.

168
00:11:21,861 --> 00:11:24,923
So we had to take picture with a real camera.

169
00:11:25,343 --> 00:11:27,084
Then I've done scanned.

170
00:11:27,744 --> 00:11:29,946
We had one scanner in Infogrames.

171
00:11:30,566 --> 00:11:32,367
So, and then try to...

172
00:11:33,113 --> 00:11:35,313
make my routines fit.

173
00:11:35,353 --> 00:11:41,274
But my 3D projection system was very, very too simple.

174
00:11:41,434 --> 00:11:45,075
And with the camera and the wide angle

175
00:11:45,135 --> 00:11:49,876
needed to have some nice large enough view,

176
00:11:50,676 --> 00:11:54,357
it was really not possible with the policy.

177
00:11:54,417 --> 00:11:58,277
So what I thought at this time, say, OK,

178
00:11:59,117 --> 00:12:01,198
I need undrawn backgrounds.

179
00:12:03,090 --> 00:12:10,216
And so, the tool, Sanedit, which was meant for, put the collision on real pictures,

180
00:12:10,336 --> 00:12:16,381
actually was used to create the rooms of the room.

181
00:12:17,842 --> 00:12:20,944
And you see how it works just after.

182
00:12:21,903 --> 00:12:25,147
At this time, at Infograms 2, they had a trainee programmer.

183
00:12:25,568 --> 00:12:27,330
They didn't know what to do with him.

184
00:12:27,390 --> 00:12:29,112
Say, OK, do you need somebody?

185
00:12:29,132 --> 00:12:30,434
Say, OK, great.

186
00:12:31,175 --> 00:12:32,116
Give me Frank.

187
00:12:32,316 --> 00:12:35,800
And Frank DeGiulami worked on this tool.

188
00:12:36,101 --> 00:12:36,241
And

189
00:12:39,155 --> 00:12:42,779
It will be the project manager for the second one.

190
00:12:42,919 --> 00:12:45,982
But OK, we are preview of that.

191
00:12:46,802 --> 00:12:49,465
So as you see here on the screen,

192
00:12:49,745 --> 00:12:52,748
that's the kind of view that Senedit generated.

193
00:12:52,768 --> 00:12:59,154
It was a wire-frame cube describing the collisions

194
00:12:59,214 --> 00:13:02,176
and all the walls and floor of the room.

195
00:13:03,250 --> 00:13:09,534
And it was not an official project at this time at Infogrames, so I was just working

196
00:13:09,594 --> 00:13:10,195
on my idea.

197
00:13:10,415 --> 00:13:11,395
I didn't believe in it.

198
00:13:12,016 --> 00:13:13,297
And so I had an idea.

199
00:13:13,317 --> 00:13:20,362
I created with this tool the first room, actually not the first room of the game, a room for

200
00:13:20,622 --> 00:13:21,082
testing.

201
00:13:22,643 --> 00:13:26,946
And I put those four camera views on a floppy disk.

202
00:13:27,915 --> 00:13:32,437
And I gave it to all the artists, to the artists in Infogrames,

203
00:13:32,617 --> 00:13:36,539
telling them, OK, I want to work with somebody who

204
00:13:36,579 --> 00:13:38,140
is really motivated.

205
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:40,141
So it's not official.

206
00:13:40,261 --> 00:13:42,422
It's not from the direction, just from myself.

207
00:13:42,622 --> 00:13:47,744
If after the work you want to draw something with that,

208
00:13:48,545 --> 00:13:49,085
just do it.

209
00:13:49,105 --> 00:13:51,666
I explained to them that, OK.

210
00:13:52,792 --> 00:13:55,353
Obviously they didn't see those pictures at this time.

211
00:13:55,833 --> 00:13:58,675
I explained to them, OK, it's like a kid coloring sheet.

212
00:14:00,375 --> 00:14:01,416
Use your Deluxe Paint.

213
00:14:01,476 --> 00:14:03,157
We used Deluxe Paint at this time.

214
00:14:03,497 --> 00:14:04,958
Photoshop didn't exist, too.

215
00:14:05,578 --> 00:14:12,021
And I asked them to make things because I was also very worried about the integration.

216
00:14:12,201 --> 00:14:14,542
When you have 3D characters, low res.

217
00:14:16,083 --> 00:14:19,804
flat polygons, and I wanted to have them very well integrated.

218
00:14:20,104 --> 00:14:23,966
So I asked them, okay, you put colors on the wall,

219
00:14:24,046 --> 00:14:26,527
try to have the maximum of flat surfaces,

220
00:14:26,847 --> 00:14:30,768
but with a lot of details to make the picture

221
00:14:31,028 --> 00:14:33,369
look like a real picture.

222
00:14:36,568 --> 00:14:42,311
So I explained that. And actually, just two of them gave me an answer.

223
00:14:44,071 --> 00:14:47,693
You need to know that Infogrames was 35 people at this time.

224
00:14:48,213 --> 00:14:50,254
So it was not a huge company.

225
00:14:51,034 --> 00:14:56,156
A guy gave me some background which looked like Prince of Persia.

226
00:14:56,176 --> 00:14:58,857
It didn't fit the ambience I wanted.

227
00:14:59,557 --> 00:15:00,598
And Yael Barrows.

228
00:15:01,498 --> 00:15:07,320
We did those four pictures, the four first pictures of the prototype of the game.

229
00:15:07,600 --> 00:15:09,581
She came from a real art school.

230
00:15:11,082 --> 00:15:19,845
Same thing, at this time, school for video games or for digital graphics didn't exist.

231
00:15:20,445 --> 00:15:23,226
But in this school, they had an Amiga.

232
00:15:23,907 --> 00:15:25,187
And when she saw...

233
00:15:26,282 --> 00:15:29,243
video games of this time with tiles and sprites,

234
00:15:29,303 --> 00:15:30,263
eight colors and everything.

235
00:15:30,844 --> 00:15:33,364
She was also convinced that there is something

236
00:15:33,424 --> 00:15:35,945
to do better with video games.

237
00:15:36,425 --> 00:15:38,986
So for her, it was the perfect fit.

238
00:15:39,566 --> 00:15:40,747
So she worked.

239
00:15:42,147 --> 00:15:44,108
Actually, she went back to school

240
00:15:44,828 --> 00:15:47,649
because I also had a PC at this time, too.

241
00:15:48,749 --> 00:15:50,470
And something that you need to know

242
00:15:50,510 --> 00:15:54,071
that she became my wife and the mother of my children.

243
00:16:00,805 --> 00:16:04,486
Okay, so now I have 3D backgrounds with collisions.

244
00:16:05,647 --> 00:16:08,787
I didn't find back the wireframe of those pictures, sadly.

245
00:16:09,347 --> 00:16:15,749
Okay, so I started to make my first hero, because I needed a hero to put in those background

